Title: Introduction to Problem Solving using Application Software
Description: This course is an introduction to problem-solving techniques using popular application software suites. Students will learn to analyze problems and apply appropriate tools and techniques to solve them. The course will cover topics such as word processing, spreadsheets, databases, and presentation software.

They will also gain experience with a modern programming language, such as Python or Java.

Description: This course covers the fundamental data structures and algorithms used in computer science. Students will learn about sorting and searching algorithms, graph algorithms, and data structures like linked lists, trees, and heaps.

Description: This course provides an introduction to the principles of operating systems. Students will learn about the architecture of operating systems, including processes, memory management, and file systems. Topics covered include concurrency, synchronization, and deadlock.

Description: This course provides an introduction to database management systems. Students will learn about the design and implementation of databases, as well as techniques for querying and manipulating data. Topics covered include relational algebra, SQL, and transaction processing.

Description: This course provides an introduction to human-computer interaction. Students will learn about the design and evaluation of user interfaces, including usability testing and heuristic evaluation. Topics covered include design principles, interface styles, and interaction paradigms.

Title: Advanced Programming Techniques
Description: This course provides an introduction to advanced programming techniques. Students will learn about software engineering principles, as well as tools and techniques for building large-scale software systems. Topics covered include object-oriented programming, design patterns, and software testing.

Title: Research Project in Computer Science
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of computer science. Students will work on projects that apply and extend the knowledge they have acquired in their coursework, and will be exposed to various research methodologies.

Title: Research Project in Theoretical Computer Science
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of theoretical computer science. Students will work on projects that explore the limits of computation and study the theoretical foundations of computer science.

Title: Research Project in Computer Graphics
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of computer graphics. Students will work on projects that explore the creation and manipulation of digital images and 3D models, and will gain experience with the latest graphics hardware and software.

Title: Research Project in Information Security
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of information security. Students will work on projects that explore new and emerging threats to digital security, and will develop strategies and techniques for protecting sensitive information.

Title: Research Project in Scientific Computation
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of scientific computation. Students will work on projects that apply computational methods to problems in science and engineering, and will develop algorithms and software tools to analyze and interpret scientific data.

Title: Research Project in Software Engineering
Description: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to engage in research in the field of software engineering. Students will work on projects that develop and test new software systems and tools, and will gain experience with the latest software engineering methodologies and best practices.

Title: Research Project in Networks and Distributed Computing
Description: This course is focused on research in the areas of networks and distributed computing. Students will work in groups to design, implement, and evaluate novel systems for data communication and processing.

Title: Project in Computer Science
Description: In this course, students will work on a semester-long project related to computer science. They will choose a topic of their interest and develop a plan for implementing it. Throughout the course, they will learn about project management techniques and tools.

Title: Project in Theoretical Computer Science
Description: This course is focused on conducting research in theoretical computer science. Students will work in groups to develop and analyze algorithms and data structures for various computational problems. They will also learn about complexity theory and its applications.

Title: Project in Computer Graphics
Description: In this course, students will learn about computer graphics and work on a project related to it. They will implement various rendering techniques and create visual effects using tools such as OpenGL and WebGL. They will also learn about 3D modeling and animation.

Title: Project in Information Security
Description: This course is focused on research in the area of information security. Students will work on a project related to security and privacy of data and systems. They will analyze various threats and vulnerabilities and design and implement techniques for securing them.

Title: Project in Scientific Computation
Description: In this course, students will learn about scientific computing and work on a project related to it. They will implement numerical methods for solving various problems such as differential equations and optimization. They will also learn about parallel computing and its applications.

Title: Project in Software Engineering
Description: In this project-based course, students will learn about software engineering practices and apply them to real-world problems. They will work in teams to design, develop, and test software systems, using industry-standard tools and techniques.

Title: Project in Human Computer Interaction
Description: In this project-based course, students will learn about human-computer interaction principles and apply them to design and evaluate interactive systems. They will work in teams to create prototypes and conduct user studies, using a variety of methods and tools.

Title: Project in Networks and Distributed Computing
Description: In this project-based course, students will learn about networks and distributed computing systems and apply them to solve real-world problems. They will work in teams to design and implement network protocols and distributed algorithms, using a variety of programming languages and platforms.

Title: Introduction to Randomized Algorithms
Description: This course is an introduction to randomized algorithms, which are algorithms that use randomness to solve computational problems. Students will learn about the theory and practice of randomized algorithms, and apply them to a variety of problems in different domains.

Title: Principles of Computer Security
Description: This course is an introduction to computer security principles and techniques. Students will learn about common threats and vulnerabilities, as well as methods for protecting systems and data. They will also gain experience with tools and technologies used in the field.

Title: Network Systems Security
Description: This course is an introduction to network security principles and techniques. Students will learn about common threats and vulnerabilities, as well as methods for securing network systems. They will also gain experience with tools and technologies used in the field.

Title: Fundamentals of Social Network Analysis and Data Mining
Description: This course explores the concepts and techniques of social network analysis and data mining. Students will learn how to analyze complex networks and extract meaningful insights from large datasets. Topics covered include graph theory, clustering, classification, and association analysis.

Title: Human-Computer Interaction II
Description: This course focuses on advanced topics in human-computer interaction. Students will learn how to design and evaluate interactive systems, with an emphasis on usability and user experience. Topics covered include user-centered design, information visualization, and mobile computing.

Title: Software Engineering Project
Description: In this course, students will work on a software engineering project in a team environment. They will learn about project management, software design and development, and testing and maintenance. The course emphasizes agile development methodologies and effective communication.

Title: Special Topics in Computer Science (Retrogames)
Description: This course explores the history and development of retro video games. Students will learn about the hardware and software technologies used in classic games, and will develop their own retro-style games using modern programming tools. The course also covers topics such as game mechanics, level design, and user experience.

Title: Special Topics in Computer Science (Comp Morphodynamics)
Description: This course explores the emerging field of computational morphodynamics, which combines computer science, biology, and physics. Students will learn about the simulation and analysis of biological growth and development, with applications in medicine, agriculture, and robotics. The course covers topics such as cellular automata, reaction-diffusion models, and morphogenetic gradients.

Title: Special Topics in Computer Science (Wearable Applications)
Description: This course explores the design and development of wearable applications, which are computer programs that run on smart watches, fitness trackers, and other wearable devices. Students will learn about the unique challenges and opportunities of wearable computing, including user interface design, sensor integration, and battery management. The course covers topics such as gesture recognition, activity recognition, and health monitoring.

Title: Thinking with Data
Description: This course provides an introduction to the concepts and methods of data science. Students will learn how to formulate questions, explore data, and communicate insights using visualizations and statistical models.

Title: Data Processing and Storage
Description: This course covers the fundamentals of data processing and storage. Students will learn how to work with different data formats, databases, and cloud storage solutions.

Title: Working with Data and Visualization
Description: This course focuses on techniques for working with data and creating effective visualizations. Students will learn how to use tools like Python, R, and Tableau to explore and communicate data insights.

Title: Working with Data at Scale
Description: This course covers the challenges and opportunities of working with large-scale data sets. Students will learn how to use distributed systems like Hadoop and Spark to process and analyze big data.

Title: Private Data Management
Description: This course introduces students to various methods for managing private data, including access control, privacy-preserving data publishing, data obfuscation, and cryptography. Students will also learn about relevant ethical and legal issues related to data privacy.

Title: Ethical Hacking Laboratory
Description: This course provides students with hands-on experience in ethical hacking, including penetration testing, vulnerability assessment, and social engineering. Students will also learn about legal and ethical issues related to ethical hacking.

Description: This course covers various aspects of governance and risk management in the context of information security. Students will learn about risk assessment and management, security policies and procedures, regulatory compliance, and incident response. They will also gain an understanding of how to implement security measures in a way that aligns with business objectives.

Title: Policies, Standards and Programs
Description: This course provides students with an overview of policies, standards, and programs related to information security. Students will learn about various industry standards, such as ISO 27001 and NIST, and best practices for implementing them. They will also gain experience in developing security policies and programs that are tailored to organizational needs.

Description: This course covers the formal methods used in software development, including mathematical models and techniques for software specification, verification, and validation. Students will also gain practical experience with formal methods tools.

Title: Software Evolution and Reuse
